article.headline: Without Iverson, Sixers lose 3 of last 4
article.linkText: LeBron's 36 helps Cavs snap road futility
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- LeBron James is making the Cleveland Cavaliers his team. The star rookie made five 3-pointers and scored 36 points, helping Cleveland end its 34-game road losing streak with an 88-81 victory over the Philadelphia 76ers on Friday night. It was the Cavs' first away win since Jan. 12 at Seattle. Cleveland's road losing streak tied for the second-longest in NBA history behind Sacramento's 43-game streak in the 1990-91 and 1991-92 seasons. New Jersey also had a 34-game streak in the 1989-90 and 1990-91 campaigns. "It was great to get a road win," James said. "My teammates are seeing I'm coming into my own. I'm focused and playing hard every game." James finished 14-of-24, including 5-of-7 from 3-point range. He made all three of his free throws and had four rebounds and five assists. James, who turns 19 on Dec. 30, fell one point short of his career-best 37 against Boston last Saturday. The No. 1 overall pick has been reluctant to take on a leadership role, but is starting to take control. "I'm a natural-born leader," James said. "My teammates are coming to me now and I've been a leader all my life." The Sixers, again playing without Allen Iverson, have lost three of four. Iverson, averaging 28.9 points, has missed four of the last five games with a swollen right knee, an injury that could keep him sidelined even longer. Glenn Robinson had 18 points and Derrick Coleman added 15 for Philadelphia (13-13), which entered the night in first place in the Atlantic Division. "We couldn't get any stops in the fourth quarter," Sixers coach Randy Ayers said. "And, we didn't have the rhythm to do anything offensively." Eric Williams added 13 points and Carlos Boozer had 12 for Cleveland, which had lost 12 of 14. Former Sixer Kevin Ollie had a career-best 12 assists. The Cavs, who had trailed since the first two minutes, tied it at 57 on a 3-pointer by James late in the third quarter. James gave the Cavs a 67-64 lead on another 3 early in the fourth. His fifth 3 made it 72-66 midway through the fourth. James made a hook shot to extend the lead to 78-72 with 3:37 left, and the Sixers didn't get closer than five the rest of the way. "He's getting confidence he can make his shots," Cavs coach Paul Silas said. "He was pretty awesome." James drew cheers from the Philly fans with several superb plays. With the clock ticking down at the end of the first quarter, James stood at the top of the circle and toyed with second-year pro John Salmons. He blew past Salmons, went around Amal McCaskill and Aaron McKie and made a left-handed, reverse layup. "He can flat-out play," Salmons said. "He didn't get all that hype for nothing." The Cavs were playing for the second time since their six-player trade with Boston. New arrivals Tony Battie, Williams and Kedrick Brown combined for 21 points, 16 rebounds and three assists. The Sixers led by 14 points midway through the second quarter, but the Cavs went on an 11-2 run and pulled to 48-42 at halftime.

Game notes
When he scored 37 against Boston, James shot 10-for-20 from the floor and made 16 of his 18 free throws. ... Eagles four-time Pro Bowl quarterback Donovan McNabb had a front-row seat and received a long standing ovation from the crowd. Wide receiver Freddie Mitchell also was in attendance. McNabb also came to last week's game against Denver to see rookie Carmelo Anthony. ... Williams had nine points in the third quarter. ... The Sixers shot 51.6 percent (33-of-64). The Cavs shot 47.9 percent (35-of-73).
